      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and im kinda confused. i've been making my payments on time every month but the actual principal balance is barely moving down. can u explain how the interest part works mathematically? why does it feel like so little of my money is actually going toward the loan itself?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, and it's almost entirely due to the way compound interest works on a loan. When you make a payment, the first chunk of that money always goes to covering the interest accrued for that specific month, which is calculated as your remaining principal balance multiplied by your interest rate. Since your balance is high at the start, the interest amount is huge, leaving very little \"leftover\" to actually reduce the principal.\n\nThink of it like a giant, hungry goblin named \"Interest\" who eats your entire paycheck before you can pay off the debt. As long as you have a large balance, that goblin is voracious and consumes a significant portion of every payment. Only once the principal balance drops down to a certain level does the goblin become less hungry, allowing more of your payment to actually chip away at the debt itself.\n\nMathematically, if your interest rate is 5% annually, that's roughly 0.41% per month. If you owe $20,000, that single month's interest is about $82. If your monthly payment is only $200, then $82 vanishes into the goblin's mouth, and only $",
