      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so as the balance gets smaller, the interest amount gets smaller too, right? so eventually i'll hit a point where most of my payment goes to principal. do you have a way to calculate or estimate when that \"tipping point\" actually happens?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that is exactly right, and you can estimate that tipping point by looking at the \"break-even\" point in your amortization schedule. This is the specific month where your monthly payment amount exactly equals the interest accrued for that month. Before this month, you are paying interest; after this month, you are finally paying down principal.\n\nTo find this number, you can use a simple formula: divide your total monthly payment by your monthly interest rate. For example, if you are paying **$400** per month and your interest rate is **5% annually** (which is roughly **0.4167%** per month), the math is $400 / 0.004167. This calculation tells you that you will hit the tipping point when your principal balance drops to approximately **$96,000**.\n\nOnce your balance falls below that number, the interest portion of your payment shrinks while the principal portion grows. However, if you are paying a smaller amount, like **$200**, that tipping point happens much earlier, around a balance of **$48,000**. You can also check your specific loan's amortization table; look",
